[Chattering]

02:58.011 --> 02:59.928
[Man]
Charles. That's not being chivalrous.

03:00.013 --> 03:02.848
[Woman] Don't worry, Mr. Wilcox.
There's no place in this game for chivalry.

03:02.932 --> 03:05.642
It tends to bring out
the animal in all of us.

03:05.727 --> 03:09.021
[Chattering Continues]

03:09.105 --> 03:11.773
Evie, not fair!

03:11.858 --> 03:15.068
[Chattering Continues]

04:38.403 --> 04:40.904
[Woman] "Dearest Meg,
I'm having a glorious time.

04:40.989 --> 04:42.656
"I like them all.

04:42.740 --> 04:45.867
"They are the very happiest,
jolliest family that you could imagine.

04:45.952 --> 04:48.412
"The fun of it is that
they think me a noodle...

04:48.496 --> 04:50.414
[Chuckling]
"And say so...

04:50.498 --> 04:52.666
"at least Miss Wilcox does.

04:52.750 --> 04:55.752
"Oh, Meg. Shall we ever
learn to talk less?

04:55.837 --> 04:59.172
"Oh. But, Meg. Meg,
dearest, dearest Meg...

04:59.257 --> 05:02.592
"I don't know what to say.
Or what you will say.

05:02.677 --> 05:04.886
"Paul Wilcox and I are in love.

05:04.971 --> 05:06.930
We are engaged."

05:09.100 --> 05:12.436
- Annie.
- Well! You Schlegel girls.

05:12.520 --> 05:16.273
- Tibby, look.
- Margaret, if I may interfere.

05:16.357 --> 05:19.276
- What on earth is going on?
- I —

05:19.360 --> 05:23.697
I can tell you nothing. Aunt Juley.
I know no more than you do. I —

05:23.781 --> 05:28.035
We only met the Wilcoxes last spring
while we were hiking in Germany.

05:28.119 --> 05:30.037
Oh, dear.

05:30.121 --> 05:33.248
Obviously. Someone must go down to
this Howards House and make inquiries.

05:33.333 --> 05:36.501
- Howards End.
- No, Margaret, inquiries are necessary.

05:36.586 --> 05:39.212
What do we know about these Wilcoxes?
Are they our sort?

05:39.297 --> 05:42.299
- Are they likely people?
- But. Aunt Juley...

05:42.383 --> 05:44.551
what does it matter?

05:44.635 --> 05:48.180
Helen's in love.
That's all I need to know.

05:50.433 --> 05:52.976
Would you please get me
a train timetable, dear?

06:11.329 --> 06:13.497
- Morning.
- Morning.

06:17.710 --> 06:19.211
Paul?

06:22.882 --> 06:25.467
[Man]
I'm afraid Crane has reported sick again.

06:25.551 --> 06:28.220
But he was to take me
to the Warringtons today for tennis.

06:28.304 --> 06:31.765
- I told him.
- He's shamming. Of course.

06:31.849 --> 06:34.226
You should get rid of him, Father.
Hire a new chauffeur.

06:34.310 --> 06:36.812
[Motor Running]

06:36.896 --> 06:38.814
Mother, we're off. Good-bye.

06:38.898 --> 06:41.400
Charlie, Charlie. Wait. Wait!

06:41.484 --> 06:43.402
- What?
- Is Papa there?

06:43.486 --> 06:46.822
Wait a minute.
We've got some cherries.

06:49.367 --> 06:52.702
[Chattering, Indistinct]

06:54.414 --> 06:56.373
Dad?

06:58.793 --> 07:00.794
Evie.

07:00.878 --> 07:02.796
All right. We're off.

07:02.880 --> 07:05.006
- Bye.
- Bye-bye.

07:09.387 --> 07:11.888
- About last night —
- Nothing happened.

07:14.058 --> 07:16.935
- I'm afraid I lost my head, rather.
- Yes, we both did.

07:17.019 --> 07:20.856
It must have been the moonlight.
Except there was no moon.

07:20.940 --> 07:23.233
Well, that's quite all right.

07:25.903 --> 07:27.904
- Do you mind?
- No.

07:34.579 --> 07:38.999
You see. I've no money of my own,
and I still have to make my way in Nigeria.

07:40.001 --> 07:42.377
It's beastly out there for
a white woman, what with the climate...

07:42.462 --> 07:44.754
and the natives and all that.

07:46.299 --> 07:49.551
- I say, I do think you're a ripping girl.
- It's quite all right.

07:49.635 --> 07:51.595
No one knows about it.

07:52.972 --> 07:56.016
- Meg! I wrote to my sister.
- Oh. No. You didn't.

07:56.100 --> 07:58.435
Yes. I'm sorry.
Look. She's sure to come down.

07:58.519 --> 08:01.396
- We must stop her.
- We'll have to send a telegram.

08:01.481 --> 08:03.982
- Oh, Crane's off sick.
- Isn't there a bicycle?

08:04.066 --> 08:05.984
Oh, yes. There is, somewhere.

08:15.620 --> 08:18.413
That will be one
and threepence, halfpenny. Sir.

08:18.498 --> 08:22.834
[Helen] M.J. Schlegel,
Six Wickham Place, London, West.

08:24.128 --> 08:26.546
Dear Meg, all over.

08:26.631 --> 08:28.465
Wish I'd never written.

08:28.549 --> 08:31.218
Tell no one. Helen.

08:56.327 --> 08:59.496
Excuse me. I'm looking for
somewhere called Howards House.

08:59.580 --> 09:02.082
- My parcel?
- The porter has it.

09:02.166 --> 09:05.168
Mr. Wilcox.
This lady wants Howards End.

09:06.504 --> 09:10.549
Forgive my asking. Are you
the younger Mr. Wilcox, or the elder?

09:10.633 --> 09:13.510
The younger. Ah.

09:13.636 --> 09:16.972
This station's abominably organized.
If I had my way. The whole lot of them
should get the sack.

09:17.056 --> 09:19.558
- Thank you. Bernard.
- Thank you. Sir.

09:19.642 --> 09:23.228
Perhaps I should introduce myself.
I am Miss Schlegel's aunt.

09:23.312 --> 09:25.730
Oh. Rather. Yes.
Miss Schlegel's stopping with us.

09:25.815 --> 09:28.275
- Do you want to see her?
- Well. That would be very nice. Yes.

09:28.359 --> 09:30.360
I could run you up in the motor.

09:37.702 --> 09:40.328
All the Schlegels are exceptional.

09:40.413 --> 09:45.125
They are. Of course, British to the
backbone but their father was German...

09:45.209 --> 09:48.336
and that is why they care
for literature and art.

09:48.421 --> 09:50.088
Uh, just one minute.

09:54.635 --> 09:56.636
Wilcox, Howards End.

09:56.721 --> 10:00.265
I'd like you to know that
I come in no spirit of interference.

10:00.349 --> 10:02.934
I'm here to represent the family...

10:03.019 --> 10:06.479
and to talk to you
about Helen. Mr. Wilcox.

10:06.564 --> 10:08.815
My niece and you.

10:08.899 --> 10:11.985
Miss Schlegel and, uh, and myself?

10:12.069 --> 10:14.070
[Aunt Juley] I trust there's been
no misunderstanding.

10:14.155 --> 10:16.406
Well. It is true that
I am engaged to be married...

10:16.490 --> 10:18.992
but to another young lady.
Not to Miss Schlegel.

10:19.076 --> 10:22.662
Helen wrote to us, Mr. Wilcox.
She has told us everything.

10:22.747 --> 10:26.124
Good God. It's some foolery of Paul's.

10:27.126 --> 10:30.003
- But you are Paul.
- No. I'm not.

10:30.087 --> 10:32.464
- Then why did you say so at the station?
- I said nothing of the sort.

10:32.548 --> 10:34.591
- I beg your pardon. You did.
- I beg your pardon, I did not.

10:34.675 --> 10:36.468
My name is Charles.

10:36.552 --> 10:39.512
Do you mean to tell me that
Paul and your niece have —

10:39.597 --> 10:41.514
The idiot!

10:41.599 --> 10:43.558
Damn fool!

10:43.643 --> 10:46.269
Look. Uh, I warn you.

10:46.354 --> 10:48.897
It's useless.
Uh, Paul hasn't a penny.

10:48.981 --> 10:52.275
No need to warn us.
The warning is all the other way.

10:52.360 --> 10:56.529
But he hasn't told us, whereas your niece
has lost no time in publishing the news.

10:56.614 --> 11:00.241
If I were a man. Mr. Wilcox,
for that last remark, I'd box your ears.

11:00.326 --> 11:02.410
You're not fit to sit
in the same room as my niece...

11:02.495 --> 11:04.913
- All I know is she spread the news —
- Or to clean her boots.

11:04.997 --> 11:06.665
- Might I finish my sentence, please?
- No!

11:06.749 --> 11:08.708
I decline to argue with such a person.

11:08.793 --> 11:11.670
- Let me out of this car this instant!
- Don't try and stand up!

11:11.754 --> 11:13.713
- Stop! Stop!
- Sit down. Sit down!

11:13.798 --> 11:15.507
- Stop!
- Just sit down!

11:15.591 --> 11:17.509
For goodness sakes!

11:17.593 --> 11:19.803
Just —

11:27.937 --> 11:29.979
[Bicycle Bell Ringing]

11:43.285 --> 11:45.203
Push it down.

11:50.418 --> 11:52.335
Oh, Helen.

11:53.754 --> 11:55.672
It's all right.

12:02.638 --> 12:06.683
[Classical On Piano]

12:23.868 --> 12:26.035
[Continues]

12:33.544 --> 12:35.879
It will, I think.
Be generally admitted...

12:35.963 --> 12:41.342
that Beethoven's Fifth Symphony
is the most sublime noise...

12:41.427 --> 12:45.388
ever to have penetrated the ear of man.

12:45.473 --> 12:47.390
What does it mean?

12:47.475 --> 12:50.560
We can hardly fail
to recognize in this music...

12:50.644 --> 12:52.979
a mighty drama:

12:53.063 --> 12:56.816
The struggle of a hero
beset by perils...

12:56.901 --> 13:01.196
riding to magnificent victory
and ultimate triumph...

13:01.280 --> 13:05.909
as described in the development
section of the first movement.

13:05.993 --> 13:08.036
What I want to draw
your attention to now...

13:08.120 --> 13:10.997
is the third movement.

13:11.081 --> 13:15.585
We no longer hear
the hero, but a goblin.

13:15.669 --> 13:17.712
Thank you, Mother.

13:19.256 --> 13:23.843
- [Mid-Tempo]
- A single. Solitary goblin...

13:23.928 --> 13:27.847
walking across the universe...

13:27.932 --> 13:30.308
from beginning to end.

13:36.106 --> 13:39.317
- Why a goblin?
- [Stops]

13:39.401 --> 13:42.445
- I begyour pardon?
- Why a goblin?

13:42.530 --> 13:44.447
Well, it's obvious.

13:44.532 --> 13:47.325
The goblin signifies
the spirit of negation.

13:47.409 --> 13:50.870
But why specifically a goblin?

13:50.955 --> 13:55.875
Panic and emptiness.
That is what the goblin signifies.

13:55.960 --> 13:57.919
Minor, spelling panic.

13:59.421 --> 14:02.048
Major, magnificent.

14:02.132 --> 14:06.135
- [Resumes]
- A hero, triumphant.

14:09.598 --> 14:11.516
Miss.

14:11.600 --> 14:13.643
Excuse me. Miss. My umbrella.

14:19.650 --> 14:21.609
Miss.

14:33.330 --> 14:35.665
[Thunder Rumbling]

14:40.504 --> 14:43.715
Miss! Miss!

14:47.928 --> 14:49.846
[Church Bells Ringing]

